<TEXT>
hostages freed in algiers from a hijacked kuwait 
airways jet came home thursday to a tumultuous reception by 
thousands of people after being released by nine shiite moslem 
gunmen who slipped away 
western diplomatic sources said they had clear evidence the 
hijackers had reached beirut after algerian officials allowed them 
to go free ending the 15day siege 
in its friday editions the new york times quoted unnamed arab 
officials as saying the hijackers had been flown on a private 
algerian jet to damascus syria and were believed to have then 
traveled over land to beirut 
the emir of kuwait sheik jaber alahmed alsabah and crown 
prince sheik saad abdullah alsabah led a group of government 
officials and relatives who were at the kuwait airport to meet the 
former captives 
flocks of doves soared over the airport as the kuwait airways 
boeing 707 carrying the 22 passengers and seven crew members 
touched down thursday night after a sixhour flight from algiers 
two other hostages released early wednesday were saudi arabian 
citizens and were flown home in a private executive jet 
bedouin men danced and clapped at the kuwaiti airport and 
children waved flags and sang god bless our father jaber 
referring to the emir 
the kuwaiti passengers traveled by motorcade to the city center 
thousands of people lining the route tossing roses and confetti 
hundreds of others followed in cars and limousines honking 
their horns and singing we sacrifice blood and souls for you o 
kuwait 
the gunmen who killed two hostages while the hijacked jumbo jet 
was in cyprus last week disappeared before dawn wednesday after 
abandoning their attempt to force kuwait to release 17 proiranian 
terrorists jailed for bombing the us and french embassies in 
kuwait in 1983 both slain captives were kuwaitis 
kuwait refused any concessions to the hijackers but algeria 
apparently promised them passage to a country of their choice if 
they freed the hostages unharmed 
algeria criticized by the united states and other western 
governments has refused to acknowledge making a deal with the 
hijackers there was no reference to them thursday in any of the 
north african countrys statecontrolled media 
several of the returning kuwaiti passengers accused iran of 
complicity in the hijacking saying one gunman was replaced by two 
others when the craft landed in iran 
one of the two was obviously a military pilot he was ordering 
other gunmen around and telling them lots of things about the 
aircraft and supervising the wiring of explosives to most parts of 
the plane said passenger khaled nasser alzaferi 
in algiers a brief farewell was held at the houari boumedienne 
airport before the former hostages were flown to kuwait 
the former captives included three cousins of sabah jaber sabah 
ruler of the sheikdom 
compared with their tense trembling appearance when they had 
emerged from the hijacked boeing 747 the former captives looked 
rested and relaxed 
anware sabah second cousin of the emir said the hijackers 
treated her and her sister with deference and without 
brutality their brother fadel khaled sabah said he was 
psychologically fatigued when he made a statement by radio to 
the control tower asking that the gunmens demands be met 
after their release the hostages spent 30 hours at the algiers 
military hospital being examined 
a kuwaiti doctor said all were in good physical condition but 
the psychological effects of the long terrifying confinement may 
be felt for weeks or months 
algerian authorities would not permit journalists to inspect the 
hijacked plane which awaited a relief crew to return it to kuwait 
one kuwait airways official said the hijackers deliberately damaged 
the radio equipment before leaving 
a member of the airport cleanup crew said trash was strewn 
through the aircraft ropes had been used to divide the seating 
area and a large world map had been pinned to the wall of the 
forward cabin he said the stench of rotting fruit filled the plane 
other arab countries including kuwait praised algeria for 
achieving freedom for the hostages without additional violence 
algerian media called it a victory but secretary of state 
george p shultz prime minister margaret thatcher of britain and 
other western leaders criticized algeria for allowing the hijackers 
to get away 
the united states will not rest until the terrorists the 
murderers the hijackers are brought to justice said state 
department spokeswoman phyllis oakley in washington 
she declined to say what steps might be taken but said officials 
are checking to see whether laws apply that allow charges against 
hijackers when a us citizen is involved at least one passenger 
carried an american passport 
an international convention calls for sanctions against any 
country allowing hijackers to escape unpunished including an end 
to direct air service to the offending nation algeria is not a 
signatory 
an sovietbuilt antonov transport of the algerian air force was 
seen taking off before dawn wednesday shortly before the hostages 
left the hijacked plane it was widely assumed the hijackers were 
aboard the antonov which can land on a grassy field 
</TEXT>
