<TEXT>
one in an intermittent series of ap candidate closeup stories 
exploring the careers and backgrounds of the remaining presidential 
contenders this story focuses on jesse jacksons record running 
operation push 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
i like everything you said the old man told 
jesse jackson on the campaign trail but wont the 
republicans be able to clobber you and the democratic party on the 
basis of your lack of governmental experience 
jackson looked around the hall he was in a new york suburb 
addressing senior citizens who had just listened to a litany of 
legislative accomplishments from sen albert gore jr one of his 
rivals for the presidential nomination 
jackson was ready for this often asked question in the first 
place he said the reaganbush administration has experience and 
look what theyve done a record trade deficit a record debt a 
mess in central america and the middle east and the most sleaze 
and corruption in american history 
then he launched into his own record of leadership in civil 
rights and labor strife 
of those of us who are running if you were about to lose 
your farm had to face the banker which one would you choose to 
argue your case if you needed a scholarship for your child who 
would you want to argue your case if you had a relative in a 
foreign jail who would you send to bring your relative back home 
now the punchline some office holders are not leaders and 
some leaders are not office holders i am a leader 
jackson has never been elected to office or run a business but 
he has headed a nationwide organization the chicagobased 
operation push people united to serve humanity and its 
educationoriented affiliate push for excellence or pushexcel 
his handling of things at push has come under scrutiny for signs of 
how he might run the government 
over the years jackson has used push to keep himself in the 
spotlight with his crowdstirring oratory mediawise instincts and 
ability to capitalize on the latest public issues 
although he stepped down as head of push when he ran for 
president in 1984 he often returns to lead its saturday morning 
meetings 
jackson was the architect of pushs campaign to pressure 
corporations to expand hiring and business opportunities for 
minorities 
however jackson left push with a record of improper use of 
government money high staff turnover and dwindling revenues 
his supporters point to pushs achievements in strengthening 
black economic power as examples of jacksons ability and say he 
was a genius at keeping the organization afloat despite a chronic 
cash shortage 
they dismiss administrative problems as mstakes made by 
wellmeaning volunteers and lowpaid staff members 
i think he managed incredibly well given the resources he had 
all civil rights organizations have always operated at a deficit 
said sam tidmore a founding member of pushs board 
jacksons critics maintain that push operated like a personality 
cult built around jackson rather than a wellmanaged organization 
jesse just doesnt have the ability to keep things together 
said the rev hosea williams a longtime civil rights activist and 
jackson critic when it comes to building and motivating people 
jesse is a genius but he cant sustain an effort and that is 
evidenced by push 
in the past decade push has been beset by troubles 
push for excellence either misspent or failed to account for 
12 million out of an estimated 66 million in federal grants 
from the departments of labor education commerce and health and 
human services federal auditors found the government still is 
trying to collect the money without having to take push to court 
the commerce department concluded in a 1980 audit that 
pushexcels accounting system and internal controls are not 
adequate to safeguard its assets or ensure reliable accounting 
and operating efficiency 
pushexcel and operation push were hit in the 1970s and early 
1980s with more than a dozen lawsuits by businesses seeking payment 
of overdue bills for such things as telephone service printing and 
paper supplies 
in jacksons 1984 campaign it was revealed the push 
organizations had received a 10000 donation from libya and 
200000 from the league of arab states the contributions were 
made after jackson toured the middle east in 1979 and was 
photographed embracing yasser arafat head of the palestine 
liberation organization 
clovis maksoud the arab leagues ambassador to the united 
nations said recently that the contribution was made because of 
a growing affinity between the arabamerican and black 
communities at that time 
maksoud said the arab league has not donated any money since 
then to the push network 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

