<TEXT>
a volunteer program backed by the 
local roman catholic church has been launched to prepare chileans 
for their first election in 15 years and organizers hope calm the 
countrys stormy political waters 
however the effort already has stirred up controversy of its 
own drawing fire from backers of the rightwing military 
government which charges that it favors the opposition 
leaders of the program called the crusade for citizen 
participation say they hope to recruit 200000 volunteers across 
the country for a doortodoor campaign starting in july they say 
the aim is to promote voter registration and to provide electors 
with nonpartisan information about their options 
most people want a peaceful transition to democracy the 
crusades director monica jimenez said in an interview its 
our task to see that this happens 
she said the crusades participants also will monitor the 
elections outcome to ensure that it is respectable and 
respected 
the government plans a yesorno ballot later this year on a 
single presidential candidate to be picked by the chiefs of the 
armed forces and national police no date has been set 
president augusto pinochet the rightwing army commander who 
seized power in a 1973 coup is seen as the most likely candidate 
in order to win the candidate must garner 50 percent of the yes 
vote plus one 
if the candidate wins he will begin an eightyear term in march 
1989 if he loses an open election will be held in early 1990 and 
pinochet will remain in power in the meantime according to chiles 
1980 constitution 
the countrys last election was in march 1973 the military 
government has held and won two referendums on political or 
constitutional questions 
mrs jimenez a university professor and social worker active in 
church affairs said she came up with the idea for the crusade a 
year ago under the auspices of a churchrun foundation she 
studied similar projects in other countries they included 
argentina and uruguay which have returned to civilian rule in 
recent years as well as the united states 
i had trouble crystallizing the idea so it helped a great 
deal to visit and study similar programs elsewhere she said 
she obtained a 1 million grant from the interamerican human 
rights institute based in costa rica to print educational 
material train volunteers and pay for television and radio 
publicity 
the training manuals for volunteers quickly prompted charges of 
bias from progovernment sectors for instructing that in part a 
yes vote means giving support to the operation of a 
presidentialist authoritarian regime characterized by a regime 
of limited citizen participation 
a no vote means reestablishing a balance of powers and 
eliminating the control by the armed forces over civilian 
authorities the instructions say 
citing the material a commentary in the governmentrun 
newspaper la nacion complained of the crusades slanted 
tendentious and partisan spirit 
its leaders dont even bother to disguise their opposition 
tendencies the commentary said 
mrs jimenez responded because we live in such a polarized 
atmosphere to talk of democracy is to already take a side this is 
the difficulty we are facing 
she said describing the pinochet government as authoritarian 
is a fact not a value judgement im not using it in the 
pejorative sense 
the crusade appears highly organized several supervisors said 
they took part in organizing pope john paul iis april 1987 tour of 
chile and were drawing on that experience 
at a roman catholic retreat in punta de tralca a coastal 
community 60 miles west of santiago hundreds of firstlevel 
volunteers from across the country receive intensive training in 
threeday sessions they are required to recruit other volunteers 
in their regions who in turn will seek out more participants in 
each community 
when the voting takes place the crusade will be out to try to 
ensure that there is no undue pressure from any sector she 
said 
the punta de tralca training sessions have a distinct catholic 
missionary flavor upon graduation the trainees sing a religious 
hymn and are given neckerchiefs of yellow and white the vatican 
colors the crusades logo of the same colors is in the shape of 
a cross 
chile like other latin american countries is overwhelmingly 
catholic 
at the end of one recent training session a santiago priest 
the rev pedro arregui told the volunteers they were like 
lights small and fragile that are going to light up chile from 
end to end 
you are carriers of a great message a message that should 
change this nation he said 
above him a broad banner quoted pope john paul ii chile has a 
vocation of comprehension not confrontation 
mrs jimenez said a central goal of the crusade is to inject 
some reason into chiles highly impassioned political arena where 
pro and antigovernment sectors wildly sling charges at each other 
for the opposition pinochet is a bloodstained tyrant while he 
calls opposition leaders the selfish pawns of international 
communism 
an important number of people have already decided whether to 
vote yes or no mrs jimenez said but when you talk to them 
you realize that often they are decisions of an emotional not 
rational basis 
the more rational the political debate the less likely it is 
that turmoil will break out when the election is decided she said 
we are trying to promote proper civic behavior 
</TEXT>
