the house foreign affairs subcommittee on asian affairs took no 
action on the measure which would require declassification of more 
data about socalled live sightings 
the defense department still lists 2404 us personnel as 
unaccounted for 13 years after the war ended president reagan has 
said an accounting is of the highest national priority 
the official us position is that the administration cannot 
rule out the possibility that some americans are still held against 
their will although vietnam cambodia and laos all say they have 
no prisoners some remains have periodically been returned from the 
area 
those who believe the us government is purposefully 
withholding information about pows have cited a variety of reasons 
those include the us wish for better relations with vietnam and 
the governments refusal to admit it had left some prisoners behind 
after the official prisoner exchange in 1973 when 591 american pows 
were set free 
in recent years a number of americans have privately searched 
for americans they believe are still being held in southeast asia 
but have found nothing the us government has opposed those 
efforts 
rep jack davis rill a cosponsor of the bill said i am 
convinced of the possibility that there are prisoners of war from 
the vietnam war still alive in southeast asia and i believe that 
the bill is a critical step in raising the awareness necessary to 
find an answer and know for certain 
retired army col earl p hopper sr father of an air force 
flier shot down 20 years ago said he and other families have been 
misled by government officials about us knowledge on the powmia 
issue 
it is because of those experiences and the fact that we have 
seen evidence in the form of cia documents proving our men were 
abandoned and never negotiated for coupled with the lack of a 
competent intelligence capability focused on securing information 
on our live pows that we support the bill he said 
we are suspicious of everything government officials 
including those in the reagan administration said hopper who 
said he is chairman of an organization called the live pow 
committee which he said represents 1500 powmia family members 
but ann mills griffiths executive director the national league 
of powmia families noted that similar charges in 1983 led to a 
similar bill which was rejected by a house committee 
she added that two congressional investigations two internal 
defense department audits and a special study by lt gen eugene 
tighe usaf retired former director of the defense intelligence 
agency have completely discredited those unfounded allegations 
we have total confidence in the presidents commitment and 
determination to fulfill his pledge to act decisively on confirmed 
information she said 
karl d jackson deputy assistant secretary of defense and army 
col joseph a schlatter chief of the defense intelligence 
agencys special powmia office said publication of information 
would make it more difficult for them to gather information 
