<TEXT>
a congressional study says the superfund 
program remains a hazardous waste merrygoround posing 
longterm problems for the nation despite improvements ordered by 
congress in 1986 
dangerous chemicals that should be destroyed are instead still 
being shifted from one waste dump to another or covered with caps 
that could allow toxics to leak into water supplies according to 
the congressional office of technology assessment 
that is the major finding from an ongoing ota review of the 1986 
law congress passed to strengthen the environmental protection 
agencys frequently criticized superfund cleanup efforts 
superfund is not working joel hirschhorn a senior 
associate of the congressional office of technology assessment 
told the house public works oversight and investigations 
subcommittee on wednesday public expectations are not being met 
by the current cleanup program 
in an assessment disputed by epa officials hirschhorn said 
in too many cases little protection of public health and the 
environment is being obtained by the 16 billion superfund is 
spending each year 
one of the basic directives that congress gave epa in 1986 was 
to permanently destroy to the maximum extent practicable the 
contaminated waste found at the worst of the nations tens of 
thousands of chemical dumps 
hirschhorn said however that epa has opted for destruction 
usually by costly but effective incineration in only 20 percent of 
the cleanup plans approved since the 1986 law took effect 
more often he said waste is still being switched to other 
sites covered by caps or treated through new but unproven 
technological processes 
offsite land disposal means that the hazardous waste problem 
rides a merrygoround hirschhorn testified the problem will 
keep growing faster than the solution we are going to have 
hundreds if not thousands of sites around the country where the 
best technologies are not chosen for the cleanup 
he also had an ominous financial warning saying the otas 1985 
estimate that the nation evenutally would have to spend 300 
billion to clean up the mess may prove low 
hirschhorn who offered no new cost estimate said the otas 
studies of epas cleanup plans show some environmental problems are 
ignored in order to avoid destruction of waste 
epa decided to put a cap on the compass industries site in 
oklahoma but made no commitment to treat contaminated groundwater 
flowing into the arkansas river according to ota 
the epas cleanup plan said however the potential for future 
fires and continued offsite migration of contaminants pose adverse 
human health and environmental impacts 
hirschhorn said ota also found instances where inaccurately high 
cost estimates for incineration led epa to select cheaper but 
untested methods to destroy wastes he said ota believes that in 
these cases incineration would have cost about the same 
epa administrator lee thomas said the agency is aiming at 
permanent treatment of wastes and that a majority of the cleanups 
involve such treatment of at least a portion of the chemicals found 
at a site 
j winston porter head of epas solid waste program said the 
agency has not yet settled on a definition of permanent he 
said that if all hazardous waste at a site were destroyed only six 
or eight cleanups could be financed each year epa is under 
congressional order to have 175 underway by this october 
