<TEXT>
a researcher who gave himself an experimental 
aids vaccine still showed immune system defenses against the aids 
virus a year later thanks to booster treatments scientists 
reported today 
but the booster procedure must be simplified before it could be 
used in largescale tests to see if the vaccine can actually 
prevent aids virus infection they said 
we are in the process of finding an easier way said daniel 
zagury of the pierre and marie curie university in paris who made 
headlines in march 1987 by reporting that he and some volunteers 
had been given the vaccine 
it was the first reported human test of a vaccine against 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome there have been no side 
effects he said 
the vaccine was essentially a vaccinia virus genetically 
modified to produce an aids virus protein called gp160 the idea 
was that the immune system would react to the protein raising 
defenses that also might fight the aids virus 
in last years report zagury and coauthors said the vaccine 
made his immune system produce two kinds of defenses proteins 
called antibodies and special blood cells 
evidence of defenses appeared up to 370 days after the initial 
vaccination he and his colleagues wrote in todays british journal 
nature but there is no proof that the zagury could have resisted 
infection by the aids virus he and 16 scientists from belgium 
zaire and the national cancer institute in bethesda md wrote 
zagury received three booster treatments 
about three months after the vaccination blood cells were drawn 
from him and infected with more modified vaccinia virus then the 
cells were reinjected through a slowdrip intravenous line a 
process that took about 3 hours zagury said in a telephone 
interview 
the second and third boosters were injections of the aids virus 
protein given 299 days and 350 days after the initial vaccine two 
unvaccinated volunteers who received only the protein shots showed 
no immune system response 
zagury showed antibodies against the aids virus protein 13 days 
after the first booster a reaction lasting three months nine days 
after second treatment more antibodies against the aids virus 
protein and against a viral protein made from it called gp120 
appeared those levels rose after the third booster 
tests at various times showed that under certain conditions 
immune system factors in zagurys blood inhibited two dissimilar 
strains of the aids virus from infecting cells in the test tube 
each booster treatment also markedly increased the ability of 
zagurys immune system cells to proliferate when exposed to either 
strain in the test tube in addition his immune system cells could 
destroy virusinfected cells for a time after each booster 
treatment 
in another test doses of aids virus protein were injected just 
under the surface of zagurys skin before the second booster and 20 
days after the third his immune system reacted each time showing 
it was still primed 
the process of removing treating and reinjecting immune system 
cells would be too cumbersome to use in a largescale experiment 
as would be required to test the vaccines effectiveness zagury 
said 
bernard moss an american aids vaccine expert said the fact 
that zagurys immune system acted against quite different strains 
of the aids virus is significant 
many previous studies suggested that a vaccine using one strain 
might not work against other strains of the highly variable aids 
virus said moss chief of the laboratory of viral diseases at the 
national institute of allergy and infectious diseases 
</TEXT>
