<DOCNO> AP880421-0091 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the federal government is moving to legalize a 
common supermarket practice giving out rainchecks or substitutes 
when a store runs out of advertised items 
while an effective date has not been announced the federal 
trade commission voted 32 wednesday to permit substitutes and 
rainchecks at grocery stores 
many stores of all types have been making such offers for years 
of course but technically the practice was made illegal for 
grocery stores in 1971 
in that year the commission adopted a regulation requiring that 
grocers have enough stock on hand to meet reasonably anticipated 
demand for advertised items those that run out can be fined 
though that has rarely happened in practice 
under the change approved wednesday grocers that dont want to 
offer substitutes or rainchecks would be allowed to advertise items 
in limited supply if they clearly state in the ads that supplies 
are limited 
the 1971 rule was adopted following studies that showed as much 
as 10 percent of advertised items were unavailable in markets in 
the 1970s 
by 1984 however that rate had dropped to between 3 percent and 
5 percent and the commission began to reconsider the rule 
the commission staff at that time reported that the costs to 
supermarkets of observing the rule keeping added stock on hand 
and perhaps limiting advertising raised the cost of groceries 
more than the sale prices lowered them 
in other words the staff said the rule was forcing consumers 
to pay an extra 14 cents to 33 cents a week in their grocery bill 
on that basis some commission staffers recommended abandoning 
the rule altogether an approach that drew heavy negative public 
comment in 1984 
nonetheless commissioner terry calvani pressed again wednesday 
to have the entire rule repealed 
i dont believe there is a problem he said contending that 
supermarket managers strive to please their customers rather than 
injure them 
in such a competitive business if a market regularly failed to 
stock advertised items customers would just stop shopping there 
he said 
commissioner andrew j strenio though contended that the rule 
simply requires retail food markets to honor the promises they 
make in advertising 
strenio added that he is skeptical of the statistics that show 
the cost of the rule to be more than the savings to consumers and 
said he opposed any changes in the rule that has been in effect 
since 1971 
thus calvani and strenio voted against the amendment to permit 
substitutions and rainchecks but for opposite reasons 
voting for the new rule were commissioners mary azcuenaga and 
patricia l bailey and chairman daniel oliver 
oliver said he would prefer to join calvani in eliminating the 
rule altogether but since that option had been defeated on an 
earlier ballot he would support the amendment permitting use of 
rain checks or substitutes in order to give grocers as much 
flexibility as possible 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

