<TEXT>
president pw botha said 
thursday he would push for black participation in cabinetlevel 
policymaking and on the electoral college that selects the 
president 
botha aides called the proposals outlined in a speech to 
parliament a major reform initiative but they fell far short of 
black demands for full voting rights and abolition of apartheid 
legislation 
the increasingly powerful farright conservative party which 
opposes any concessions to blacks assailed the speech the 
conservatives koos van der merwe urged botha to resign and said 
the presidents colossal lack of political credibility had made 
him an object of ridicule among his fellow afrikaners 
bothas proposals appeared unlikely to ease international 
pressure on south africa for an end to apartheid which establishes 
racially segregated neighborhoods hospitals and schools gives the 
5 million whites almost total political control and deprives the 26 
million blacks of a vote in national affairs 
but domestically bothas message was that his national party 
would not back off from slowpaced reform despite the 
conservatives victories in three recent parliamentary byelections 
if the white people do not wish to follow my way it is their 
responsibility botha said if they follow the way of 
confrontation it is their problem 
bothas proposal to include blacks in the electoral college 
would if implemented mark the first time that blacks had a direct 
voice in the selection of south africas president he gave no 
details about how many seats blacks might have in the college 
which has 88 members 50 of them from the national party 
botha suggested that a cabinetlevel executive authority be 
opened to people not serving in parliament this would clear the 
way for participation in policymaking by blacks who are excluded 
from parliament 
botha also reiterated his longstanding proposal for creation of 
a national advisory council on which he and top cabinet ministers 
would negotiate with black leaders on drafting of a new 
constitution that would bring blacks into the central government 
we are not committed to the name the form the composition or 
the functions of such a body he said we are committed to the 
concept of a forum for deliberation 
he said black leaders were unhappy with the term national 
council and suggested that their reluctance might be overcome by 
calling the forum the great indaba indaba is a zulu word for a 
tribal assembly 
most prominent black leaders have rejected overtures to 
participate in the council saying the government first must free 
imprisoned black nationalist leaders such as nelson mandela and 
lift restrictions on major antiapartheid organizations 
mangosuthu buthelezi chief minister of the kwazulu homeland and 
a leading black moderate said bothas electoral college proposal 
amounted to tokenism because the national party does not 
admit to the existence of a black majority in south africa 
but buthelezi praised botha for finding the courage to confront 
the far right 
now that he has taken a first tentative step to defy the 
conservative party let him be bold and be explicit about how 
far he is prepared to go 
helen suzman veteran parliament member for the liberal 
progressive federal party criticized botha for not setting a 
timetable for his proposals she said he was evading the question 
of black participation in parliament 
botha became prime minister in 1978 that postition was 
abolished in 1984 with the adoption of a new consititution and he 
was installed as president 
in his speech botha proposed that the office of prime minister 
be revived to handle daytoday government affairs while the 
president concentrates on major policy matters and ceremonial 
duties 
