<TEXT>
a japaneseamerican living in japan said thursday 
he expects to receive an apology for being interned in the united 
states during world war ii but not to get reparations as approved 
by the us senate 
barry saiki 68 a retired us army officer working in public 
relations in japan said reparations were justified because 
japaneseamericans lost possessions and five years of their lives 
i think well get the apology saiki said in a telephone 
interview but he said he thought president reagan would veto the 
bill that eventually emerges from congress 
the chance that congress would overturn a presidential veto was 
slim he said therefore the possiblity of getting the reparation 
is rather questionable 
the senate passed a bill wednesday to give an apology and 
20000 in taxfree payments to japaneseamericans who were rounded 
up and placed in camps after the japanese attack on pearl harbor on 
dec 7 1941 the house passed a similar bill in september 
the japanese government had no official reaction to the senate 
action because it was a domestic us issue foreign ministry 
spokesman yoshifumi matsuda told reporters 
but matsuda said he personally praised the senate action because 
he had been a consul general at the japanese consulate in los 
angeles and had worked on the issue 
after many years the justness and fairness are recovered 
through democracy matsuda said this is the way of american 
democracy 
saiki said he and his family were uprooted from their california 
home in 1942 like thousands of other japaneseamericans who fell 
under suspicion after the attack on pearl harbor 
he had been about to graduate from the university of california 
at berkeley but instead ended up in a camp in arkansas with his 
mother and two younger brothers his father was sent to a separate 
camp for community leaders he said 
saiki was inducted into the us army in 1944 and was 
commissioned as an officer just as the war ended his family was 
able to move to philadelphia where they worked as farm laborers 
living in the basement of an old house 
after the war his family returned to california again working 
as farm laborers 
from the day they were evacuated in 1942 in 1947 five years 
later they hadnt gotten back to prewar status saiki said 
they had lost everything they had acquired up to 1942 i very 
definitely feel it reparations is very justified 
he said his own military career in counterintelligence brought 
him to japan on four tours after the war and he spent 10 years on 
military duty in this country then after he retired as a 
lieutenant colonel in 1966 he returned here to work and has 
remained ever since 
saiki is a member of the board of the japaneseamerican 
citizens league which has about 150 members 
some of us are not in such pressing need for money he said 
but there are others who are half the people have died and 
every year the number is getting smaller the people who deserved 
the money and who need it are gradually dying 
asked if he felt japan had a role in the issue because its 
attack on pearl harbor led to the internment he replied its an 
american problem its not because of japan that it happened 
</TEXT>
