<TEXT>
gov michael s dukakis said today we make 
history thursday as he signed into law massachusetts 
firstinthenation proposal to provide health insurance to all 
residents by 1992 
what we do here today can and must be done all over the united 
states the democratic presidential frontrunner told an 
estimated 2000 supporters crowded onto the statehouse steps for 
the signing ceremony 
today marks the day when working families the unemployed the 
disabled students and children with special needs dont go sick 
because they cant afford to stay well those days in the 
commonwealth are over he said as the crowd applauded 
from now on when the sick land at the doorstep of our health 
care system the first question of them will be where does it 
hurt not how will you pay 
only hawaii which has an exemption to federal law allowing it 
to require employer health coverage has anything comparable to the 
massachusetts law 
however the massachusetts legislation which statehouse aides 
say has generated inquiries from more than 20 states goes beyond 
hawaiis approach by offering health security both to working and 
nonworking residents 
in his speech dukakis didnt specifically mention whether he 
would seek similar federal legislation if he became president but 
he did say today we make history but there is more history to 
be made 
as an american i dont want my country to stand alone with 
south africa as the only two industrialized nations that do not 
provide basic health security for their citizens 
the bill was the outcome of a ninemonth legislative struggle 
and comes two years after massachusetts voters endorsed a 
nonbinding referendum by a 2to1 margin urging congress to 
enact a national health care program universal in coverage 
the narrowly passed the legislature last week the doubters 
said a lot of things dukakis said and they were wrong 
but doubters remain dr david u himmelstein of harvard medical 
school and spokesman for physicians for a national health program 
called the health care bill a first step but said it was a 
bandaid approach when major surgery is needed 
and house minority leader steven pierce a republican described 
the bill as shortterm gain and longterm pain mike dukakis has 
managed to pick up some shortterm political gain at the expense of 
longterm fiscal pain for the commonwealth 
on wednesday dukakis estimated that the laws cost to taxpayers 
would be 6452 million through fiscal 1992 minus about 225 
million in projected costcutting in medicaid other estimates put 
the cost to the state government in the next four years as high as 
12 billion 
the thrust of the law is to provide coverage to about 600000 
massachusetts residents under age 65 currently without health 
insurance roughly one of every 10 people in the commonwealth 
this would be done in stages and through a variety of 
approaches from extending medicaid benefits for disabled adults 
and children to statebrokered pooled insurance for small 
businesses and individuals 
by 1992 all employers with more than five fulltime employees 
must offer health insurance coverage or pay an unemployment 
surcharge to help the state provide this coverage to the uninsured 
