sen brock adams dwash seeking to force a 
senate debate on the issue of war and peace in the persian 
gulf said thursday he will introduce legislation to authorize the 
continued presence of us military forces in the gulf and set 
rules for their use 
adams said he will also seek congressional action to trigger the 
war powers act which requires the removal of us forces from 
hostile areas within 60 days unless their continued presence is 
specifically approved by congress 
in the last year we have deployed dozens of american ships in 
the gulf adams said we have spent tens of millions of 
dollars we have asked americans to sacrifice their lives 
but congress has never authorized the deployment never 
appropriated any money never clearly stated its support for the 
policy that is being followed 
adams said a number of individual senators have offered the 
administration specific suggestions on changes or modifications in 
us persian gulf policy and some are being considered seriously 
but he said that is not enough 
the senate as an institution has to give some guidance to the 
administration adams said congress has a right and a 
responsibility to debate the policy being followed by the 
administration as well as the right to consider alternatives 
only by engaging in a full and frank debate only by working 
with our colleagues and having the administration work with us can 
we refine our approach to the problem and strengthen our national 
commitment to solve it he said 
the war powers act is a postvietnam attempt to apply a 
congressional brake to unilateral presidential decisions to expose 
us forces to possible hostilities it has been resisted by the 
reagan administration as an encroachment on the presidents 
authority as the nations military commander in chief 
adams said he realizes an attempt to invoke it will be 
challenged but said the act should be implemented because it 
remains the law of the land 
i am not trying to force the withdrawal of american forces 
from the persian gulf adams said we have a right to be there 
and a mission to perform there 
adams said he is only seeking to protect the constitutional 
right of the congress to be involved in decisions to deploy us 
forces into areas of hostility 
