canada will be a full partner in the 14 billion 
space station project intended to put a manned platform in space by 
the late 1990s industry minister robert de cotret announced 
thursday 
prime minister brian mulroneys conservative government had 
delayed a decision on the project for three months after the 
estimated cost to canada over the next 17 years escalated from 648 
million us to 972 million 
de cotret said 90 percent of the money will be spent in canada 
producing 4 billion in spinoffs beneficial to science and industry 
weve got a place in space he told a news conference he 
termed the project an investment in ourselves our ingenuity and 
our brain power 
about half the extra funds required will come from a 1 billion 
science and technology fund announced by mulroney in january it 
was originally intended solely for university programs 
canadas contribution will be a roving space robot to act as the 
hands and arms of the station the computerized robot would have 
sight touch and reasoning powers and would unload cargo repair 
satellites and do other tasks 
in return canadian astronauts would have access to the station 
for about three months a year for experiments 
the largest international civilian space venture in history will 
consist of three laboratories built separately in the united 
states western europe and japan and a giant metallic living 
module made by the americans 
canada is the final partner to join the consortium 
the government has yet to decide between montreal and ottawa as 
the headquarters for the canadian space agency that will oversee 
the project most of the countrys aerospace industry is located 
near montreal 
