<TEXT>
the crew of the korean air lines plane shot 
down by soviet fighters in 1983 negligently made the flight knowing 
the navigation system was not working a lawyer for the victims 
relatives argued thursday 
donald madole lead counsel for a committee that represents the 
relatives of those killed in the sept 1 1983 crash of flight 007 
said there was abundant evidence to show that the crew chose to 
continue the flight even though it determined in alaska that the 
navigation system was not properly set before takeoff from 
anchorage 
a total of 269 passengers and crew died when the flight which 
originated in new york city was shot down over the sea of japan 
after straying off course into soviet air space 
the plane ended up 320 miles off course because the inertial 
navigation system ins had been improperly set during a fueling 
stop in anchorage madole said 
from the moment that airplane took off it was never never on 
course he told us district judge aubrey e robinson jr 
the crew deliberately attempted to conceal their failure to 
either properly stabilize the ins or set it up properly madole 
said 
the pilot and crew knew the journey without navigation guides 
would lead the plane into a dangerous area where it could be shot 
down without warning if it strayed into soviet airspace madole 
said 
