<TEXT>
for three centuries language has divided 
canadas two founding cultures the novelist hugh maclennan 
prophetically called it the two solitudes of english and french 
despite some progress toward bilingualism at a federal level as 
promised in the 1982 constitution language tensions have flared 
anew from frenchspeaking quebec to the western prairies where 
english is dominant 
a fluently bilingual prime minister brian mulroney about to 
start his reelection campaign has suddenly found himself diverted 
into quelling anglophone and francophone unrest 
three issues have converged to create the new turmoil 
the province of saskatchewan has repealed an 1886 act requiring 
it to issue laws in both english and french alberta is expected to 
do the same 
the supreme court is about to rule on quebecs controversial 
ban on english signs quebec is 81percent french but the vocal 
english minority in la belle province claims the ban violates 
freedom of speech and is unconstitutional 
