<TEXT>
generations of workers and slaves transported 
granite blocks 600 miles down the nile river to erect the 57ton 
colossus of memphis 
nearly 3200 years later sophisticated engineers at bostons 
museum of science were perplexed about how they would handle the 
giant statue honoring ramses ii the last great pharaoh of egypt 
and the empires most prolific builder 
while preparing for an exhibit of artifacts from his 66year 
reign engineers grappled with methods to bring the 27foot 
structure into the museum proposals to demolish a wall or cut a 
hole in the roof were deemed infeasible and too costly 
so we decided to put it outside said mary dussault a 
project coordinator for the ramesses the great exhibit which 
opens april 30 and runs for four months i have to say it looks 
pretty majestic 
exhibit directors use the preferred translation of the pharaohs 
name ramesses instead of the more accepted anglicized version 
ramses 
the giant statue depicts ramses wearing the coneshaped crown of 
upper egypt royalty and a pleated skirt jewels adorn his neck and 
wrist as he strides forward left foot first 
the colossus was uncovered by crews digging the foundation for a 
building in 1962 near memphis egypt it was broken into three 
large pieces and many fragments about 30 workers began to 
reassemble the statue in 1985 doing the reconstruction in the area 
where it had been discovered 
the colossus of memphis will stand outside the museum encased 
in a 40foot wood and steel structure resembling an ancient 
egyptian temple the monument is the centerpiece of the 72piece 
exhibit the largest collection of antiquities from egypts golden 
age ever on display in north america 
the ramses show is larger than the 55 artifacts seen by more 
than 8 million people in the tutankhanum exhibit which toured the 
united states and canada in the late 1970s and generated more than 
50 million 
priceless antiquities from the reign of ramses the great were 
first seen in north america in october 1985 at brigham young 
university that show went on to be displayed at the worlds fair 
in vancouver british columbia jacksonville fla and memphis 
tenn 
the three sections of the colossus and dozens of crates 
containing other artifacts from cairos egyptian museum arrived in 
boston last week from denver 
the exhibit insured by lloyds of london for 40 million was 
designed to depict the grandeur as well as the simplicity of life 
under ramses ornate jewelry including a 19pound gold necklace 
with braided collar and 14 tassels are displayed along with such 
prosaic items as a cosmetic case a bronze razor and senet a board 
game popular at the time 
theres also the lid from the mummy coffin that contained 
ramses remains the elaborate burial chamber of sannedjem a 
respected painter and artisan and several statues of baboons from 
the temple at abu simbel 
ramses left a rich legacy of monuments and buildings including 
his mortuary temple at thebes the temple of abu simbel in nubia 
two obelisks in front of the temple at luxor his palace city at 
zoan in the delta and the temple at karnak with the largest columns 
in the world they measure roughly 11 feet in diameter 
architects still marvel at the precision of abu simbel where 
sunlight streams 160 feet into the temple on certain days to 
illuminate an inner chamber 
ramses reported to have sired 90 children waged a long and 
successful battle against the hittites of palestine and is believed 
by some biblical scholars to be the pharaoh of the book of exodus 
like his prodigious family and his mammoth projects tales of 
his life ring on a grand scale ancient records say ramses claimed 
his birth was signaled by the emergence of the star sirius on the 
same day as egyptians began their religious and civil new years a 
convergence which occurs once every 1461 years 
he ruled from 12791213 bc no one is quite sure when he was 
born but he was in his 80s when he died ramses i his grandfather 
who founded the 19th dynasty after akhnaton and tutankhamen ruled 
for one year seti i ramses father waged war against libyans and 
hittites and extended the boundaries of the egyptian empire ramses 
continued war against the hittites an ancient people of asia 
minor and syria in palestine 
the battle of kadesh was one of the last battles with the 
hittites ramses ii later signed a peace treaty with the hittites 
although ramses mummy remains in cairo the boston exhibit will 
feature padihershef a 2500yearold mummy owned by massachusetts 
general hospital 
last month padihershef a stonecutter was transported from the 
hospital in a plastic bubble stretcher designed for victims of 
nuclear accidents 
jan crocker director of traveling exhibits at the museum said 
negotiations to bring the exhibit to boston were launched several 
years ago by museum director roger nichols who died in december 
after the ramses exhibit returns to egypt the colossus will 
remain in memphis tenn for six more months 
each city sponsoring the exhibit guarantees a minimum 400000 
payment to the egyptian government to help construct a new national 
museum 
