<TEXT>
rising consumer prices are contributing to worries in the 
financial markets that inflation is accelerating 
the government said wednesday that consumer prices jumped 05 
percent in march reflecting a record increase in clothing costs 
and higher food and gasoline prices that triggered the biggest 
inflation jump in 14 months 
analysts said the sharp increase in the labor departments 
consumer price index which translated into a 64 percent annual 
growth rate demonstrated that the weak dollar and unexpectedly 
strong consumer demand were threatening to ignite a new bout of 
spiraling costs 
they speculated those pressures soon would prompt the federal 
reserve to nudge interest rates higher 
the bond market a good indicator of inflation sentiment 
reacted negatively to the cpi report bond prices fell and the 
yield on the treasurys key 30year bond rose to 905 percent 
although prices later recovered somewhat 
stocks also fell wednesday pushing the dow jones industrial 
average down 1409 points to 198541 its third straight decline 
the financial markets first were jolted last week when an 
unexpectedly high us trade deficit for february sent the dollar 
plunging a government report that wholesale prices jumped in march 
intensified investor worries 
the reagan administration which is counting on the federal 
reserve to keep the economy growing through the november election 
