<TEXT>
japans economy is riding one of its biggest booms 
of the past five years surprising many economists who just last 
year were predicting a recession 
economists say the boom fueled by low interest rates tax cuts 
and massive public spending will continue for at least two years 
further into the future they say annual growth in the gross 
national product likely will exceed the governments 375 percent 
forecast for the next five years 
the speed of japans recovery has surprised most commentators 
this is really a remarkable pace said rich jerran an economist 
for the kleinwort benson investment firm the domestic economy is 
roaring 
during the past 11 months manufacturing output shot up 14 
percent a figure that took twice as long to achieve during the 
boom years of the 1970s economists say 
government officials report that corporate profits rose 272 
percent during 1987 while household savings rose by 118 percent 
inflationadjusted consumer spending rose a near record 58 
percent in february alone second only to a 59 percent rise 
recorded in november 1975 
according to the investment firm merrill lynch sustaining the 
current economic pace over the rest of 1988 would mean gross 
national product growth of 5 percent corporate profit growth of 
about 18 percent and retail sales growth of 138 percent 
william p sterling senior economist for merrill lynch in 
tokyo said japans 1987 growth alone could keep the economic boom 
rolling for the rest of this year making it a fertile market for 
the united states and other nations wanting to boost their exports 
a drop in japanese exports because of the rising yen which 
makes japanese products more expensive overseas cooled the 
economy somewhat last year but exports affect only 17 percent of 
japans gnp sterling said 
the other 83 percent is not exports and that did very well 
he said 
sterling said the current boom is the best of the past four or 
five years although the officially projected gnp growth rate of 
375 percent is low compared to the 8 percent to 10 percent a year 
japan achieved during the 1960s and part of the 1970s 
just last may economists were saying japan was headed for an 
economic downturn with the yens rapid rise inflating prices for 
the nations exportdriven economy 
industrial production fell to its lowest rate in years and 
unemployment rose to a record 32 percent japans unemployment 
rate is artificially low because it counts as employed members of 
the armed forces and people who work more than one hour during the 
last week of the month 
there was a lot of pressure to stop the yen from going up in 
1986 jerran said japan achieved this by cutting interest rates 
fueling a domestic housing boom that contributed about onethird of 
the gnp growth 
jerran said the government also injected 48 billion into the 
economy through public works spending and tax cuts 
at a news conference on tuesday bank of japan governor satoshi 
sumita said he was pleased with the economys performance and said 
one of his biggest concerns is maintaining stability 
sumita said that without a sudden appreciation in the yen or a 
rapid rise in prices economic growth was unlikely to slow 
although the united states will benefit somewhat from japans 
prosperity sterling said the effect would not be that great 
although us exports rose by 558 percent last month from a year 
earlier exports to japan still accounted for less than 1 percent 
of gross national product 
the united states needs to export not only to japan but 
everywhere else to get out of the problems it is in now he said 
one downside to the japanese economy might be in housing starts 
and the relative prosperity japan has enjoyed for the past year 
things have been so good economists say there is bound to be a 
slowdown 
the cost of housing has reached the point where it takes eight 
years of a workers gross income to purchase a small condominium 
which costs about 500000 four years is considered normal in most 
other countries 
jerran also says there is a danger of the japanese economy 
overheating 
because of the rapid rise over the past year industry is 
running out of capacity and labor he said this raises the 
danger that prices will climb upwards 
in turn the bank of japan may decide to push interest rates 
higher possibly by this summer to help curb inflation he said 
