evidence presented in newarks closely 
watched cigarette trial indicates tobacco companies conspired 
to hide the dangers of smoking and the jury trial should continue 
a federal judge declared today 
at the same time however judge h lee sarokin dismissed a 
claim that the three companies sued in the liability case liggett 
group inc philip morris inc and lorillard inc caused rose 
cipollones lung cancer by not marketing a safer cigarette 
attorneys for mrs cipollone argued that the companies knew they 
could develop a safer cigarette that had less potential of causing 
cancer mrs cipollone 64 of lakehurst died in 1984 after 40 
years of smoking 
but the judge said the attorneys for mrs cipollones estate 
carrying on a lawsuit filed before she died had not presented 
evidence to support that claim 
nevertheless sarokin of us district court said the jury 
trial will continue over whether the three manufacturers conspired 
to misrepresent and conceal facts regarding the dangers of smoking 
he also said mrs cipollones estate could continue seeking 
punitive damages 
sarokin said that the evidence indicates that the cigarette 
industry entered into a sophisticated conspiracy 
the conspiracy was organized to refute undermine and 
neutralize information coming from the scientific and medical 
community and at the same time to confuse and mislead the 
consuming public in an effort to encourage existing smokers to 
continue and new persons to commence smoking the judge said 
sarokin also said a jury might reasonably conclude that 
the defendants in particular and the industry in general 
intentionally and willfully ignored the known health consequences 
to consumers from the sale of their products 
the evidence presented also permits the jury to find the 
tobacco industry conspiracy vast in its scope devious in its 
purpose and devastating in its results the judge said 
but sarokin dismissed claims that philip morris and lorillard 
failed to warn mrs cipollone of the dangers of cigarettes 
the judge said mrs cipollone did not start smoking cigarettes 
manufactured by those two companies until she was a veteran smoker 
and the companies had no duty to warn her about any dangers until 
she became a consumer of their products 
similar claims against liggett however were allowed to 
continue 
the trial which began feb 1 is viewed by both the industry 
and smoking opponents as critical in the tobacco companies efforts 
to defend against future liability cases 
